This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with learning depth and camera ego-motion from raw RGB video streams. The paper also proposes a novel self-supervised two-stream network for accurate visual odometry, which is a common problem in computer vision. The paper also uses data augmentation and regularization techniques, which are commonly used in computer vision. 

The paper could also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as visual odometry is an important problem in robotics, and the proposed method could be useful for robot navigation. 

The paper could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it proposes a novel self-supervised learning method for visual odometry. 

The paper could also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it deals with learning from raw video streams without explicit supervision. 

Finally, the paper could also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category as it proposes a neural network-based approach for visual odometry.
